<h2>Why Character Counting Matters More Than You Think</h2>
<p>Every platform you publish on has limits. Twitter gives you 280 characters per post. SMS messages max out at 160 characters before they split into multiple segments. Google truncates meta descriptions somewhere around 155-160 characters. App Store titles cap at 30 characters. Google Ads headlines limit you to exactly 30 characters per line. If you go over these limits without knowing, your message gets cut off mid-sentence — sometimes in ways that make your brand look careless.</p>
<p>A <a href="/tools/character-counter/">character counter</a> tells you exactly where you stand before you hit publish. Not just total characters, but the breakdown: letters, digits, spaces, punctuation. Each metric answers a different question. Total characters matches what Twitter and SMS enforce. Characters without spaces helps when you're working with CJK (Chinese, Japanese, Korean) text where spaces don't separate words. The letter-to-digit ratio tells you whether your text is readable or looks like a CAPTCHA. A dedicated counter gives you all of this in real time as you type.</p>

